<p>Suppose we want to graph the following function.</p>
<div>
$$
\begin{align*}
\frac{3x-3}{-x+2}
\end{align*}
$$
</div>
<p>How can we approach this?
<br />
<br />
<!------------------------------------------------------------------------------------></p>
<h3>Vertical Asymptotes</h3>
<p>The first step is finding the asymptotes. For the vertical asymptote, we want to find what makes the denominator equal to zero. The function is already in a simple form (otherwise weâ€™d need to simplify it first (why? because the factors that cancel with the numerator will be holes in the graph rather than asymptotes)). We can then just solve,</p>
<div>
$$
\begin{align*}
-x + 2 &amp;= 0 \\
x &amp;= 2
\end{align*}
$$
</div>
<p>So \(x = 2\) will be our vertical asymptote.</p>

<p><br />
<!------------------------------------------------------------------------------------></p>
<h3>Horizontal Asymptotes</h3>
<p>Next, we need to find the horizontal asymptote. Letâ€™s revise the three cases we did before. Suppose we have the function</p>
<div>
$$
\begin{align*}
\frac{a_m x^m + a_{m-1} x^{m-1} + ...}{a_n x^n + a_{n-1} x^{n-1} + ...}
\end{align*}
$$
</div>
<p>Then,</p>
<ul>
<li> if \(m &lt; n\), then the horizontal asymptote is \(y = 0\).</li>
<li> if \(m = n\), then the asymptote is the leading coefficient of the numerator over the leading the coefficient of the denominator. \(\frac{a_m}{a_n}\). </li>
<li> if \(m = n + 1\), we will have a slanted asymptote.</li>
</ul>
<p>Here, \(m = n\), therefore, the horizontal asymptote is \(y = -3\).
<br />
<!------------------------------------------------------------------------------------></p>
<h3>Plotting points for each section of the graph</h3>
<p>After graphing the asymptotes, weâ€™ll have the following graph,</p>
<p style="text-align:center;"><img src="http://localhost:4000/assets/math/graphs/linear-over-linear/0.png" width="60%" class="center" /></p>
<p>Now, we want to find at least two points to plot for each section of the graph. Letâ€™s find the value of \(f\) for example at at 1 and -1. We can see that \(f(1) = \frac{3 - 3}{-1 + 2} = 0\) and \(f(-1) = \frac{-3 - 3}{-(-1) + 2} = -2\). For the other side, letâ€™s find \(f\) at values \(3\) and \(5\). \(f(3) = \frac{9 - 3}{-1} = -6\) and \(f(5) = \frac{15 - 3}{-3} = -4\). And now weâ€™re done!</p>

<p style="text-align:center;"><img src="http://localhost:4000/assets/math/graphs/linear-over-linear/1.png" width="60%" class="center" /></p>

